  "notes": [
    {
      "id": "note_49",
      "text": "Circular-statistics tests for phase/angle columns (radians, degrees, or clock-hours on a chosen period). The Rayleigh test always runs: for each column it asks whether the phases (e.g. acrophases, activity-onset times) point in a preferred direction rather than scattering uniformly, reporting the mean resultant length R (0 = dispersed, 1 = tightly clustered), Rayleigh's z = nR², a p-value, and an acrophase (Batschelet 1981). Wiring an optional time column — numeric hours or an actual timestamp, folded modulo the period to a clock phase — switches every column to an amplitude-weighted mode: each value weights its own measurement time's angle, giving an amplitude-weighted mean resultant vector and acrophase (the weighted mean time-of-peak) instead of treating the column as a set of raw angles; the unit setting is then ignored. An optional Watson-Williams test (toggle it on, like the boxplot's pairwise comparisons) adds the circular analogue of one-way ANOVA across the columns (each a group of raw angles), reporting an F statistic and p-value for whether the groups share a common mean direction; it assumes reasonably concentrated, similarly-dispersed samples and applies a von Mises concentration correction (Watson & Williams 1956) — it only applies to untimed columns, since it compares discrete event angles, not a continuous weighted rhythm. In the demo the two angle columns each cluster tightly (small Rayleigh p) but around different mean directions, so the Watson-Williams test is significant.",
      "x": 40,
      "y": 24,
      "width": 360,
      "height": 190
    }
